Java 21 focuses mainly on improving scalability, readability, and developer productivity.
The most important feature is Virtual Threads, which enables handling a large number of concurrent tasks efficiently.
It also introduces Pattern Matching improvements, Record Patterns, Sequenced Collections, and String Templates to reduce boilerplate code and improve readability.

🧸 1. Virtual Threads (BIGGEST FEATURE)

“How do you create Virtual Threads and how are they different?”

Say:
Virtual threads are lightweight threads managed by the JVM instead of the OS. 
Unlike platform threads, when a virtual thread performs a blocking operation,it does not block the underlying OS thread. 
Instead, the JVM suspends the virtual thread and reuses the OS thread for other tasks, enabling high scalability.

In Java 21, Virtual Threads can be created using Thread.startVirtualThread() or Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor().
They are lightweight threads managed by JVM, unlike platform threads which are OS-managed.
Virtual threads allow handling thousands of concurrent tasks efficiently because they don’t block OS threads during waiting operations,
making them ideal for IO-bound applications like microservices.

🧠 Final Analogy
Platform thread = 🚕 one taxi per person
Virtual thread = 🚆 one train carrying thousands

👶 Problem (Old Java):

Imagine you have 1000 customers calling your shop 📞
You hire 1000 workers → expensive, slow, system crashes 😵

🆕 Solution:

Java 21 gives Virtual Threads = very tiny, lightweight workers

👉 One real worker can handle MANY calls

🧠 Simple idea:
Old thread = heavy elephant 🐘
Virtual thread = tiny ants 🐜 (thousands can work together)
💻 Use Case:
APIs (Spring Boot apps)
Microservices handling many users
Chat apps, booking systems

🛠️ How to Create a Virtual Thread
✅ 1. Simplest Way (Best for interviews)

Thread.startVirtualThread(() -> {
    System.out.println("Hello from Virtual Thread");
});

👉 That’s it. No boilerplate.

✅ 2. Using Builder (More control)
Thread vt = Thread.ofVirtual().start(() -> {
    System.out.println("Running in virtual thread");
});
✅ 3. Using ExecutorService (REAL PROJECT USE 🔥)
try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
    executor.submit(() -> {
        System.out.println("Task 1");
    });

    executor.submit(() -> {
        System.out.println("Task 2");
    });
}

👉 This is what you’ll use in:

Spring Boot APIs
Microservices
Parallel calls
🤯 What Problem Does It Solve?
❌ Old Way (Platform Threads)
Each request = 1 thread
Thread is heavy (1MB memory approx)
10,000 users → 💥 crash or slow
✅ Virtual Threads
Each request = 1 virtual thread
Very lightweight
10,000 users → 😎 smooth handling
⚔️ Virtual Thread vs Platform Thread
Feature	Platform Thread 🧑‍🏭	Virtual Thread 🐜
Created by	OS	JVM
Memory	High	Very low
Count	Limited (1000s)	Millions possible
Blocking	Blocks OS thread 😓	Doesn't block 😎
Performance	Slower for high load	Very fast for high concurrency
Use case	CPU tasks	IO tasks (APIs, DB calls)
🧠 VERY IMPORTANT CONCEPT (Interview Gold)
❓ What happens when Virtual Thread waits?

Example:

Thread.startVirtualThread(() -> {
    Thread.sleep(5000);
});

👉 Does it block?

❌ Old Thread:
Yes, thread is blocked
✅ Virtual Thread:
NO ❗
JVM pauses it
Frees underlying OS thread
Uses it for other work

👉 This is called:
👉 "Non-blocking behavior with blocking code style" 🤯

🌍 Real Use Case (Spring Boot)
Problem:

You call 3 APIs:

callService1();
callService2();
callService3();

Old way → slow 😓

Virtual Thread Way:
try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {

    Future<String> f1 = executor.submit(() -> callService1());
    Future<String> f2 = executor.submit(() -> callService2());
    Future<String> f3 = executor.submit(() -> callService3());

    System.out.println(f1.get() + f2.get() + f3.get());
}

👉 All run in parallel → ⚡ fast response

🚨 When NOT to Use Virtual Threads

Don’t blindly use everywhere:

❌ CPU-heavy tasks (like calculations)
❌ tight loops (no waiting)

👉 Use for:
✅ API calls
✅ DB calls
✅ File operations
