🧸 2. Record Patterns (Smarter Data Checking)
Record patterns in Java 21 allow us to deconstruct record objects directly while performing type checks,
eliminating the need for explicit casting and making the code more concise and readable

Java 21 lets you open + check in one step

💻 Example idea:

Instead of:

check type
cast object
get values

👉 You do everything in one clean line

🧠 Use Case:
Parsing API responses
Working with DTOs
Cleaner backend code

👶 Problem (Old Way)

You have a record:

record Person(String name, int age) {}

Now you want:
👉 Check if object is Person
👉 Extract name and age

❌ Old Way (Too many steps 😓)
if (obj instanceof Person) {
    Person p = (Person) obj;   // casting
    String name = p.name();
    int age = p.age();
}

👉 Problems:

Extra casting 😵
More lines
Less readable
🆕 Solution: Record Pattern
✅ New Way (Java 21 😎)
if (obj instanceof Person(String name, int age)) {
    System.out.println(name + " " + age);
}

👉 What happened here?

Checked type ✅
Extracted values ✅
No casting needed ✅

⚡ With switch (VERY IMPORTANT 🔥)
switch (obj) {
    case Person(String name, int age) -> 
        System.out.println("Person: " + name);

    default -> 
        System.out.println("Unknown");
}

👉 This is heavily asked in interviews

🧸 3. Pattern Matching for switch (Smarter Switch)

switch can now understand types (objects), not just numbers or strings

👶 Problem:

Old switch only works with:

int
String
enum

🆕 Solution:
Now switch can understand:
objects
types
conditions

❌ Example:
Object obj = "Hello";

switch (obj) {   // ❌ not allowed before
}

👉 So we had to use messy if-else

if (obj instanceof String) {
    String s = (String) obj;
    System.out.println(s);
} else if (obj instanceof Integer) {
    Integer i = (Integer) obj;
    System.out.println(i);
}

😵 Too long, hard to read

🆕 Solution: Smarter switch 😎
✅ Now you can do this:
Object obj = "Hello";

switch (obj) {
    case String s -> System.out.println("String: " + s);
    case Integer i -> System.out.println("Integer: " + i);
    default -> System.out.println("Unknown");
}

👉 What happened?

Type check ✅
Casting ✅
Variable extraction ✅

Old switch = only understands numbers 🔢
New switch = understands objects 🧠

💻 Use Case:
Request handling
Validation logic
Business rules
